<section xml:id="sec_units" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Units</title>
  <introduction>
	
    <p>
     The measurement of any quantity is made with respect to specific standard or physical unit. When reporting a quantity, this physical unit must be specified along with the numerical value of the quantity. For example, a student in a physics lab reports that the length of an object has been measured to be 17.4, but what does this number tell us? Unfortunately, the number is meaningless unless they specify a specific unit for that measurement. They could mean that the length is 17.4 centimeters, inches or miles. 
		</p>
		
<p>
In science, we use the SI unit system (le Systéme Internationale d'Unités), also commonly referred to as the metric system. All measurements must be made with respect to some reproducible standard. The history of how standards of measurement were made is a fascinating subject. In the united States, we have an entire <url href="https://www.nist.gov/">government agency</url> dedicated to upholding standards of measurement. 
    </p>
		
		  </introduction>
			
<p>
Physical quantities can be divided into two categories: base quantities and derived quantities. Interestingly, we only need three base quantities to fully describe all quantities related to mechanics. These base quantities are length, time and mass. All other quantities are derived from these basics units. For example, the units of force are given their own name, the Newton, however, a Newton is a combination of the base units of length, time and mass. The units of energy, the Joule, are also derived from base units of length, time and mass.
</p>

